reviews.review_description:
This game is already pretty amazing, given that it’s still under development, and that it’s being made by (apparently) just one dev. 

It’s quickly becoming my favourite Quest game: the graphics are relatively simple, but feel very intentional, so it seems like a stylistic choice rather than a budget issue. 

The ships you fly are interestingly varied, the control mechanisms too-notch, and the “use fire extinguisher to repair critical damage” mechanic is exactly the right amount of stressful in the middle of a hectic battle.

And the battles! They start off small as you’re learning the controls, but they get BIG and cinematic, fast. When you warp into an area to find a line of enemy ships you have no chance against, only to be reinforced by a group of destroyers warping in beside you? OH MAN. So much fun.

That said, there are rough spots, but it’s one developer, and the game is in progress, so it’s understandable:

* The enemy ships aren’t super intelligent, so if they’re not locked onto you it can feel a bit like they’re flying in a scripted way, even though I assume they aren’t;
* The music isn’t great: I wish I could choose something different, from my library;
* Since I can’t, I just turn the music off but the game doesn’t remember the setting when I load it next (very minor gripe);
* There’s not a lot of feedback when I’m getting hit other than my console catching fire (the cockpit shaking would be fun);
* Pulling the throttle all the way back makes you go very slowly in reverse. This is fine, but I’m enjoying flying inside a capital ship’s shields and parking for a second to take out their big guns, so having a hard stop option would he appreciated;

But these are all minor nitpicks of a super fun game I am happy to help support the development of with my purchase. Can’t wait for each update!
